# issue #962 Lane 1 — root_fns isolation: a user root fn must not
# shift the typed AST of an imported module.
#
# `main` defines `fn tag(Int)` — a root shadow of the same bare name
# that `lib.driver` calls internally. Two independent facts must both
# hold:
#
#   1. `lib.driver()` stays "STR:hi": the imported module resolves its
#      own bare `tag("hi")` by narrowing, blind to the user's `tag`.
#      This is the cut — without it the typecheck of `lib` is
#      contaminated by the root fn and fails to compile.
#   2. `tag(0)` is "ROOT": the user's shadow still wins in user code.
#      The cut narrows visibility direction (core never sees user), it
#      does NOT weaken the user's own shadowing.
#
# Discriminant by construction: revert the cut and this program no
# longer compiles (type mismatch inside `lib.driver`). The
# byte-identical core-typecheck oracle lives in Lane 3.

import lib

#[doc("Adversarial root shadow of the bare name `lib.driver` calls.")]
fn tag(x: Int) : String = "ROOT"

fn main() : Unit / Stdout = {
  println(lib.driver())
  println(tag(0))
}
